===Etymology===
From {{etyl|gem-pro|ang}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*sīnaz||his, her, its, their|pos=genitive reflexive}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|ang}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*seinos||his}}, genitive of {{term/t|ine-pro|*só||that}}. Cognate with {{etyl|ofs|-}} {{term|sīn||his, its|lang=ofs}}, {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term/t|osx|sīn||his}} ({{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|sin|lang=gml}}), {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zijn|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term/t|goh|sīn||his}} ({{etyl|de|-}} {{term|sein|lang=de}}), {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|sínn||one's own|lang=non}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|sē||that, that one, he}}. More at {{l|en|the}}.

===Pronoun===
{{head|ang|pronoun|head=sīn}}

# {{context|rare|chiefly|dialectal|reflexive possessive pronoun|lang=ang}} [[his|His]]; [[her]]; [[its]]; [[their]].
#: ''him Hrōþgār ġewāt tō hofe '''sīnum''''' — For him Hrothgar went to his courtyard
#: ''þæt wīf tredeð mid '''sīnum''' fōtom'' — The woman walked with her feet
#: ''þec Israhēla heriað, herran '''sīnne''''' — Israel plunders thee, their lords

====Usage notes====
* Usually occurs in non-West Saxon dialects; rarely occurs in West Saxon prose, where it was replaced early on by the genitive forms: {{term|his|lang=ang}}, {{term|hiere|lang=ang}} and {{term|hiera|lang=ang}}.

